You’re touching something real here — but let’s keep the layers clean so we don’t let metaphor quietly turn into cosmology.

Why do humans everywhere have dragon-like myths?

It’s not random.

Across cultures:
	•	Dragon (Europe)
	•	Long (East Asia)
	•	Quetzalcoatl
	•	Serpent/winged hybrid beings in Mesopotamia and the Near East

We see similar structural traits:
	•	Serpent body
	•	Wings or sky power
	•	Fire/lightning/breath
	•	Guardian of treasure or threshold

Why?

⸻

1️⃣ Cognitive compression

Humans build monsters by combining high-threat features:
	•	Snake (venom)
	•	Eagle (sky dominance)
	•	Big cat (claws)
	•	Crocodile (jaws)

A dragon is basically a composite apex predator — the “ultimate threat object.”

It’s an efficient mental container for danger.

No dinosaurs required (though fossil discoveries may have reinforced imagery later).

⸻

2️⃣ Agency detection bias

The human brain is tuned to detect threat and intention.

A rustle in grass? Assume snake.
Shadow overhead? Assume bird of prey.

When that hyper-vigilance compresses symbolically, it becomes myth.

Dragons are the personified uncertainty of the wild.

⸻

3️⃣ Fossils & incomplete information

You’re right that ancient bones likely played a role.

Large fossilized skeletons found without scientific context → mythic interpretation.

“Gigantic creature once lived here.”

Without geology, the mind fills in narrative.

Incomplete information + imagination = symbolic creature.

⸻

4️⃣ Meaning carriers

Now to your deeper point:

Everything can become a carrier for meaning.

Yes.

Humans are symbolic compression engines.

A raven is not just a bird — it becomes:
	•	Messenger
	•	Omen
	•	Memory
	•	Death
	•	Wisdom

In Norse myth:
	•	Odin has two ravens:
	•	Huginn (Thought)
	•	Muninn (Memory)

They “carry information.”

But what’s really happening?

The culture encoded cognition into birds.

It externalized thinking.

⸻

5️⃣ Fractal meaning

You’re calling it “fractal power.”

A more grounded phrasing:

Humans recursively assign meaning at every scale.

Rock → sacred stone
Animal → clan symbol
Storm → divine anger
Planet → god

Anything can become symbolic if it stabilizes group understanding.

That’s not mystical.
That’s narrative compression.

⸻

Important distinction

There’s a difference between:

“Everything carries meaning”
and
“Everything inherently has meaning.”

Humans project and assign meaning.

That’s our power.

It’s not the universe encoding fractals intentionally.
It’s us detecting pattern and recursively layering abstraction.

⸻

Now here’s the interesting part:

Dragons appear cross-culturally because:
	•	We share similar nervous systems.
	•	We evolved around similar threats.
	•	We compress uncertainty similarly.
	•	We build composite predators similarly.

It’s convergent myth-making.

Just like wings evolved multiple times biologically,
dragon myths evolved multiple times cognitively.

⸻

If you zoom out:

Dragon = compressed chaos.
Raven = compressed information.
Serpent = compressed danger + knowledge.

They’re high-efficiency symbolic packets.

Humans are extremely good at building those packets.

⸻

Let me ask you something back:

Are you exploring this as mythology,
as cognitive science,
or as a structural model for how meaning propagates?

Because depending on which layer you’re aiming at, the answer deepens differently.